          "body": "The military crisis is produced by Jehoram's own strategic choice. He selects the wilderness of Edom — politically clever, geographically lethal. Seven days of marching through waterless desert consumes the army before battle begins. Jehoram's response in 3:10 is theologically revealing: 'Alas! For the LORD has called these three kings to give them into the hand of Moab.' He invokes Yahweh's name to interpret the crisis as divine abandonment. His theological instinct is not wrong — Yahweh is sovereign over this — but his response is despair, not petition. Jehoshaphat's response is the chapter's hinge: 'Is there not a prophet of the LORD here, that we may inquire of the LORD by him?' (3:11). The same crisis, two responses. One king reads the problem as God's sentence; the other reads it as an occasion for prophetic inquiry. The chapter argues that Jehoshaphat's instinct is the correct one — not because it produces an immediately comfortable answer, but because it connects the coalition to the only resource that can actually help them."
