          "body": "Elisha is identified to the coalition not by his title or his miracles, but by his service: 'who used to pour water on the hands of Elijah' (3:11). This is the chapter's portrait of prophetic greatness — faithfulness in menial obscure service. His reception of Jehoram is blunt: 'What do I have to do with you? Go to the prophets of your father and your mother' (3:13). Elisha will not be a court resource available to royal convenience. He serves because of Jehoshaphat alone (3:14), and he serves the God before whom he stands — 'Yahweh of hosts,' the divine commander of armies (3:14). Before the oracle comes, a minstrel is summoned. When the music plays, 'the hand of the LORD came upon him' (3:15). This detail resists systematizing: the Spirit's coming is not mechanically produced by music, but the music creates a posture of spiritual receptivity in which the prophetic word arrives. The oracle that follows is twofold: immediate water without natural cause (3:16-17) and military victory as 'but a slight thing' in Yahweh's sight (3:18-19). The juxtaposition — impossible water supply is trivial to God, the entire Moabite nation is trivial to God — reframes the coalition's catastrophe as an opportunity for divine display."
