          "body": "Water arrives at dawn, at the precise moment of the morning sacrifice, from the direction of Edom — with no wind, no rain, no visible meteorological cause (3:20). The fulfillment is exact in both detail and timing. The same water that saves the Israelite army destroys the Moabite plan. When the Moabites rise early and the rising sun strikes the water, it appears 'red as blood' (3:22). Their interpretation — that the three allied kings have turned on each other in the night — is plausible enough to send them rushing toward what they expect to be plunder. They run into an ambush. The chapter then narrates the systematic destruction of Moab's land: cities struck, trees felled, springs stopped, fields ruined with stones — the precise catalogue of destruction Elisha's oracle had specified (3:19, 25). The miracle of provision and the deception of the enemy are the same event, seen from opposite perspectives. Yahweh used one act to accomplish two purposes simultaneously — a pattern of providential economy characteristic of 2 Kings' theology."
