        "title": "The king who half-reformed — partial obedience as theological category",
        "range": "3:1-3",
        "excerpt": "He did evil in the sight of the Lord, though not like his father and his mother; for he put away the sacred pillar of Baal… Nevertheless, he clung to the sins of Jeroboam.",
        "body": "The narrator's formula for evaluating Israelite kings in 2 Kings operates on a two-axis grid: Yahweh's eyes (the divine standard, 3:2) and the benchmark of precedent kings (Jeroboam's baseline for the north, David's for the south). Jehoram scores better than Ahab on the first axis — he removes the *matstsevah* (standing stone) of Baal, the most visible symbol of Ahab and Jezebel's cult-importation — but fails on the second. He 'clung' (*davaq*) to Jeroboam's sins.\n\nThe Jeroboam standard in Kings is the golden calves at Bethel and Dan, installed by the first northern king to prevent his subjects from making pilgrimage to Jerusalem (1 Kings 12:26-33). These were not Baal worship — they were Yahwistic iconography, likely bulls as pedestals for the invisible Yahweh, but Deuteronomy categorically forbade them (Exodus 32; Deuteronomy 4:15-20). Jehoram's retention of this system is the narrator's signal that the reform was cosmetic. He removed the foreign cult item; he kept the indigenous syncretism.\n\nThis distinction matters theologically for the entire chapter. When crisis comes in 3:10, Jehoram's response is despair rather than petition. A king who has never genuinely aligned his institutional life with Yahweh cannot draw on the covenantal relationship in crisis. His theology in 3:10 and 3:13 is not wrong in content — Yahweh is sovereign — but it is the theology of an observer, not a covenant partner. He knows Yahweh exists and rules; he does not know Yahweh as the one before whom he stands.\n\nChuck Swindoll (Hand Me Another Brick) notes that Jehoram's reform typifies the most dangerous form of religiosity: enough change to silence conscience, not enough to transform character. The Baal pillar is removed; the golden calves remain. The chapter's opening three verses predict everything that follows.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Davaq* (clung, 3:3) — the covenant-cleaving word of Deuteronomy 10:20 ('You shall fear the LORD your God; you shall serve Him and cling to Him') — appears here with bitter irony. The same verb calibrated for devotion to Yahweh describes Jehoram's tenacious devotion to Jeroboam's sin. *Matstsevah* (sacred pillar) — the standing stone or stele associated with Baal worship, categorically prohibited in Deuteronomy 16:22."
