        "excerpt": "But Jehoshaphat said, 'Is there not a prophet of the Lord here, that we may inquire of the Lord by him?'",
        "body": "The military narrative of 3:4-10 establishes the political background and the crisis by stages. Mesha's rebellion (3:5) is the occasion; Jehoram's coalition-building (3:6-7) is the response. Jehoshaphat's reply to Jehoram in 3:7 — 'I am as you are, my people as your people, my horses as your horses' — is word-for-word the reply he gave Ahab before the disastrous battle of Ramoth-gilead (1 Kings 22:4). The repetition is the narrator's ironic signal: Jehoshaphat is doing it again, joining a northern coalition without consulting Yahweh first. His godly instinct (seeking a prophet) arrives late — after commitment, not before.\n\nThe chapter's theological pivot is the word 'but' (*wa-*) introducing Jehoshaphat's question in 3:11. Against Jehoram's despair, Jehoshaphat redirects the coalition to prophetic inquiry. The servant's identification of Elisha is striking in its specificity: not 'Elisha the great prophet' or 'Elisha who did mighty works,' but 'Elisha the son of Shaphat, who used to pour water on the hands of Elijah' (3:11). Greatness in the prophetic tradition is indexed to faithful service, not to platform.\n\nElisha's reception of the three kings (3:13-14) is a masterclass in prophetic independence. He will not perform on command for Jehoram. His dismissal — 'go to the prophets of your father and mother' — distinguishes the true prophet from the court prophets who had served Ahab's religious apparatus. Douglas Stuart (WBC, Hosea-Jonah) notes that the prophets of Baal and Asherah were specifically available to royalty for consultation; Elisha makes clear he is not in that category. He serves Yahweh of hosts (*tsava*), the divine commander of heaven's armies — not the commander of Israel's armies.\n\nThe condition of 3:14 — 'were it not that I regard the presence of Jehoshaphat' — is one of the chapter's most significant theological statements. Jehoshaphat's covenantal faithfulness mediates prophetic access for an unworthy coalition. This is not a one-time novelty; it is a canonical pattern. In Genesis 18, Abraham's righteous intercession protects Lot's city. In Numbers 14, Moses' intercession prevents immediate destruction of the nation. One man's covenantal standing extends provisional benefit to those around him. The oracle is given to the coalition not because it deserves it, but because a righteous king is present.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yehovah tsava* (LORD of hosts, 3:14) — the divine title combining Yahweh's covenant name with His role as commander of the heavenly and earthly armies. *Navi* (prophet, 3:11, 13) — the authorized spokesman, the one who 'stands before' (*amad liphnei*) the LORD — the same posture Elisha claims in 3:14 as his credential."
